e 3^t \ \ \ \  orall n,d,u,t\in\mathbb{N}$$ Where we let $\mathbb{N}$ denote positive integers. I am not confident there is no counterexample. Edit, My attempted If $u=4k-1$ then $\sum_{q=0}^{u}(n+qd)^{2}
e 3^t $ Formula $$ \sum_{q=0}^{u}(n+qd)^{2} =n^2(u+1)+d(2n+d) rac{(u+1)u}{2} +d^2 rac{(u+1)u(u-1)}{3} \  \ \ \ \  \  ...eq(1)$$ Proof Let's suppose $\sum_{q=0}^{u}(n+qd)^{2}=3^t $ By $eq(1)$ we can write $2×3^{t+1}=6n^2(u+1)+3d(2n+d)(u+1)u+2d^2(u+1)u(u-1)$ Now consider $u=4k-1$ $\implies  3^{t+1}=12n^2k+6d(2n+d)k(4k-1)+8d^2k(4k-1)(2k-1) $ We know $12n^2k=even$ $6d(2n+d)k(4k-1)=even$ $8d^2k(4k-1)(2k-1)=even$ And $even +even +even =even
e 3^{t+1}$ It's show complete proof for $u=4k-1$
